<HEADLINE>
<P>
GORBACHEV AND SOVIET REFORMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to "A Step for World Safety, If East Bloc Is Serious," by Ernest 
Conine, Op-Ed Page, Oct. 17: 
</P>
<P>
Conine goes into all kinds of reasons that the Russians want to join with the 
United States to fight international terrorism, something at which they have no 
peer. However, "In view of the nationalist fervor now sweeping the Soviet Union 
. . . " describes the true -- and sole -- reason for their sudden change of 
heart towards terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
The Russians will simply tag the term "terrorist" to describe nationalist 
freedom fighters who want to free their once-independent countries from the 
Russian stranglehold. Will the U.S. participate in helping the Russians put 
down a fight for the independence these people have waited and fought for so 
long? Will everyone who ever wanted to regain self-determination be 
automatically labeled a "terrorist?" 
</P>
<P>
I am certain that few freedom-striving people would want to spill their own 
(and other people's) blood in the quest for independence, but they will if they 
have to. Nothing comes easy, especially your freedom. Where will the U.S. stand 
on this issue? 
</P>
<P>
NORMAN MacPHERSON 
</P>
<P>
Palos Verdes 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
